@austerity and @Khalid Back down to my original 1% Big weekend for MIXED messages! I may be way off but, I might have been too quick to change my mind on the weekend positive noises from NOIC comments. So, here goes. I'll try to avoid being too slow to change my mind again knowing full well I could be dead wrong.  Conclusion: Iran and SA are odds with each in the run up to this OPEC meeting. The Saudis are attempting to undercut Iran price wise. Iran may or may not be willing to "freeze" &, at what levels... are all open questions. Summing up the contravening longer term approaches taken by both major players, without a MAJOR Saudi concession,  the circumstantial evidence that follows leaves LITTLE ROOM for an agreement by Iran to cap its oil output before 17/16; especially considering the new Saudi weekend developments. Here is why. A. POST Moshan Qamsari's @ NIOC comment on Friday that Iran had already reached a desirable level of output of around 4.2mbpd to proceed with freezing its production; NB: he did make clear such as decision had to be taken by the oil minister himself....http://www.presstv.ir/Detail/2016/05/06/464312/Iran-says-ready-to-join-oil-freeze-plan/ 1. This weekend: Iran's Oil Minister Zangeneh quoted by IRINN television as saying Tehran will not accept any plan entailing freezing of oil production.
http://m.sputniknews.com/business/20160508/1039281707/iran-wont-freeze-oil.html 2. 9/5/16: TASNIM News Sunday Oil Minister Zangeneh  complained oil customers being lured away by Saudis offering LOWER prices to the customers looking for Iran's oil. He once again rejected a proposed oil freeze plan by OPEC noting Saudi obstinacy as above mentioned. http://www.tasnimnews.com/en/news/2016/05/09/1070259/saudis-luring-oil-customers-away-from-iran-minister 3.Additionally, and CRITICAL to this GJ Q w/in the 1/7/16 time line, the Saudi's on the other hand, post this weekend departure of al-Nami and, the  appointment of Al-Falih close to deputy crown prince  Mohammed bin Salman, have two important objectives: a) Saudis don't want Iran to be free to ramp up oil production ( while the rest of OPEC hold their revenue in check) & b) Prince Salman's SA VISION 2030 of weaning itself off of oil production is a statement in and of itself - lower oil prices might even help his reform agenda; http://finance.yahoo.com/news/saudi-minister-believer-reform-low-oil-price-022818070.html ; http://qz.com/678568/we-could-be-in-for-an-even-wilder-ride-on-oil-prices-now-that-a-30-year-old-saudi-prince-is-in-charge/
http://www.wsj.com/articles/saudi-oil-ministers-exit-tightens-princes-grip-1462709963

My standard non-zero opening gambit. The following has likely been posted before, but I thought that I might draw your attention to two items contained therein: http://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-03-13/iran-on-oil-freeze-leave-us-alone-until-production-higher First:
"The last time production exceeded 4 million barrels a day was in August 2008, and Iran’s output in February was 3 million barrels a day, according to data compiled by Bloomberg....Iran is seeking to boost output by 1 million barrels a day by June, Seda Weekly reported, citing an interview with Amir Hossein Zamaninia, Iran’s deputy oil minister for commerce and international affairs." And secondly;
"Iran’s oil exports will rise to 2 million barrels a day in the month ending March 20, the end of the Iranian year, from 1.75 million barrels a day a month earlier, Zanganeh said, according to ISNA."  Now, please define which production number will be used by the Iranians to reach their 4MM bpd production threshold. Is it the internally stated production number, which may only refer to a theoretical capacity for export and may not actually reflect barrels leaving a wellhead, or is it the exportable oil number which reflects the capacity of their infrastructure to actually deliver the 4MM bpd? If we are talking exportable oil, which is the only meaningful datapoint for this IFP as it would be the only oil impacting world markets, (although the threat of unleashing additional oil in the markets can be useful, see the price capping ability of domestic shale) then a growth rate of 0.25MM bpd over the prior month, unless such was to increase markedly, would make one think that it might be well beyond the end of June to achieve the 4MM bpd production point.
